@opencatbox
@category{Package grobner}
@closecatbox

@end deffn

@c -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
@anchor{poly_gcd}
@deffn {Function} poly_gcd (@mvar{poly1}, @mvar{poly2}, @mvar{varlist})

Returns the greatest common divisor of @mvar{poly1} and @mvar{poly2}.

See also @mrefcomma{ezgcd} @mrefcomma{gcd} @mrefcomma{gcdex} and
@mrefdot{gcdivide}

Example:

@example
(%i1) p1:6*x^3+19*x^2+19*x+6; 
                        3       2
(%o1)                6 x  + 19 x  + 19 x + 6
(%i2) p2:6*x^5+13*x^4+12*x^3+13*x^2+6*x;
                  5       4       3       2
(%o2)          6 x  + 13 x  + 12 x  + 13 x  + 6 x
(%i3) poly_gcd(p1, p2, [x]);
                            2
(%o3)                    6 x  + 13 x + 6
@end example

@opencatbox
@category{Package grobner}
@closecatbox
@end deffn

@deffn {Function} poly_grobner_equal (@mvar{polylist1}, @mvar{polylist2}, @mvar{varlist})
@code{poly_grobner_equal} tests whether two Groebner Bases generate the same ideal.
Returns @code{true} if two lists of polynomials @mvar{polylist1} and @mvar{polylist2}, assumed to be Groebner Bases,
generate the same ideal, and @code{false} otherwise.
This is equivalent to checking that every polynomial of the first basis reduces to 0
modulo the second basis and vice versa. Note that in the example below the
first list is not a Groebner basis, and thus the result is @code{false}.

@example
(%i1) poly_grobner_equal([y+x,x-y],[x,y],[x,y]);
(%o1)                         false
@end example

@opencatbox
@category{Package grobner}
@closecatbox

@end deffn

@deffn {Function} poly_grobner_subsetp (@mvar{polylist1}, @mvar{polylist2}, @mvar{varlist})

@code{poly_grobner_subsetp} tests whether an ideal generated by @mvar{polylist1}
is contained in the ideal generated by @mvar{polylist2}. For this test to always succeed,
@mvar{polylist2} must be a Groebner basis.

@opencatbox
@category{Package grobner} @category{Predicate functions}
@closecatbox

@end deffn

@deffn {Function} poly_grobner_member (@mvar{poly}, @mvar{polylist}, @mvar{varlist})

Returns @code{true} if a polynomial @mvar{poly} belongs to the ideal generated by the
polynomial list @mvar{polylist}, which is assumed to be a Groebner basis. Returns @code{false} otherwise.

@code{poly_grobner_member} tests whether a polynomial belongs to an ideal generated by a list of polynomials,
which is assumed to be a Groebner basis. Equivalent to @code{normal_form} being 0. 

@opencatbox
@category{Package grobner}
@closecatbox

@end deffn

@deffn {Function} poly_ideal_saturation1 (@mvar{polylist}, @mvar{poly}, @mvar{varlist})
Returns the reduced Groebner basis of the saturation of the ideal
@iftex
@tex
$$I(polylist):poly^\infty$$
@end tex
@end iftex

@ifnottex
I(polylist):poly^inf
@end ifnottex

@noindent
Geometrically, over an algebraically closed field, this is the set
of polynomials in the ideal generated by @mvar{polylist} which do not identically
